[[File:Friedrich Uebelhoer.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Brigadeführer]] Friedrich Uebelhoer]] '''Friedrich Uebelhoer''' (born 25 September 1893 in [[Rothenburg ob der Tauber]], [[Kingdom of Bavaria|Bavaria]] – presumed died 1945) was a [[Germany|German]] politician and official with the [[Nazi Party]].
==Early life== Uebelhoer served as an officer in the [[German Imperial Army]] in the [[First World War]].<ref name="Unger">Michal Unger, ''Reassessment of the Image of Mordechai Chaim Rumkowski'', Wallstein Verlag, 2004, p. 24</ref> He joined the Nazi Party initially in 1922 then again in 1925, following the revocation of the ban placed on the group after the [[Munich putsch]].<ref name="Klee">Ernst Klee, ''Das Personenlexikon zum Dritten Reich. Wer war was vor und nach 1945'', Fischer Taschenbuch Verlag, Zweite aktualisierte Auflage, Frankfurt am Main 2005, p. 633.</ref>
He became [[Kreisleiter]] in [[Naumburg (Saale)]] in 1931.<ref name="Klee"/> He was Mayor of Naumburg from 1933 to 1939 and also served as head of the [[National Socialist People's Welfare]] in Gau Halle-Merseburg.<ref name="Klee"/>
==SS activity== Uebelhoer held the rank of [[Brigadeführer]] in the [[Schutzstaffel]] and received commendation for his involvement in the annexation of the [[Sudetenland]] and for his part in the [[Anschluss]].<ref name="Unger"/> Following the occupation of [[Poland]], he served as an inspector in the [[Reichsgau Wartheland]].<ref name="Klee"/> In [[Łódź]] he ordered the construction of the [[Łódź Ghetto|Jewish ghetto]] on December 10, 1939, a measure he described as only temporary, adding that ultimately the Nazis intended to "burn out this plague dump".<ref>Willi Jasper, "[http://www.zeit.de/1995/29/Wozu_noch_Welt_?page=all ‚Wozu noch Welt?‘]", ''Die Zeit'' 1995</ref>
In early October 1941, Uebelhoer drew the ire of [[Reinhard Heydrich]] when he vehemently protested against the intended deportation of 60,000 German Jews to the already overcrowded ghetto. In letters to one another, Heydrich threatened to draw "appropriate conclusions" if Uebelhoer did not change his stance. Through negotiations with [[Adolf Eichmann]], the number eventually reached was 20,000 Jews and 5,000 Gypsies sent to Łódź, with tens of thousands sent to other ghettos.{{sfn|Gerwarth|2011|p=205}}{{sfn|Longerich|2012|p=546–47}} In November that year, to assuage Uebelhoer's qualms about ghetto arson started by Gypsies, [[Heinrich Himmler]] advised Uebelhoer to shoot ten Gypsies for every fire that broke out within the ghetto. Those Gypsies who did not perish in the Łódź Ghetto were killed by gas vans in January 1942 in [[Chełmno extermination camp|Chełmno]].{{sfn|Longerich|2012|p=669}}
Uebelhoer was dismissed from his post as governor of Łódź in December 1942 after being accused of embezzlement by [[Arthur Greiser]].<ref name="Unger"/> The charges were ultimately unproven, but the suspicion damaged his reputation and halted his advancement in the SS.<ref name="Unger"/> He would return in January 1944 in the lesser role of governor of the [[Merseburg]] district.<ref name="Unger"/>
Uebelhoer disappeared in the latter days of the [[Second World War]] and remained unaccounted for. He was declared legally dead in 1950.<ref>[http://www.redcap70.net/A%20History%20of%20the%20SS%20Organisation%201924-1945.html/U/UEBELHOER,%20Friedrich.html UEBELHOER, Friedrich]</ref>
