'''Logical holism''' is the belief that the world operates in such a way that no part can be known without the whole being known first. [[Bertrand Russell]] concluded that "[[Hegel]]'s [[Hegelian dialectic|dialectical]] logical holism should be dismissed in favour of the new logic of [[propositional analysis]]."<ref>Michael Baur (ed.), ''G. W. F. Hegel: Key Concepts'', Routledge, 2015, p. 193.</ref>
